19: Remove Nth Node From End of List
Problem Statement

Given the head of a linked list, remove the nth node from the end of the list and return the modified head.

Examples
Input: head = [1,2,3,4,5], n = 2
Output: [1,2,3,5]
Input: head = [1], n = 1
Output: []
Intuition

Instead of calculating the length of the linked list first, we can use the Two Pointer (Fast & Slow Pointer) technique.

The idea is to maintain a gap of n + 1 nodes between the fast and slow pointers.

When the fast pointer reaches the end of the list:

The slow pointer will be positioned just before the node that needs to be removed.

This allows us to delete the target node in a single traversal.

Approach
Step 1: Create a Dummy Node

A dummy node simplifies edge cases, especially when the head node needs to be removed.

ListNode dummy = new ListNode(0);
dummy.next = head;

Example:

dummy -> 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 -> 5
Step 2: Initialize Fast and Slow Pointers
ListNode fast = dummy;
ListNode slow = dummy;

Both pointers start at the dummy node.

Step 3: Move Fast Pointer Ahead

Move the fast pointer n + 1 steps ahead.

for(int i = 0; i <= n; i++) {
    fast = fast.next;
}

This creates a fixed gap between fast and slow.

Step 4: Move Both Pointers Together
while(fast != null) {
    fast = fast.next;
    slow = slow.next;
}

When fast reaches null, slow will be just before the node to remove.

Step 5: Remove the Target Node
slow.next = slow.next.next;

This skips the target node and removes it from the list.

Step 6: Return the Updated Head
return dummy.next;
Code
class Solution {
    public ListNode removeNthFromEnd(ListNode head, int n) {

        ListNode dummy = new ListNode(0);
        dummy.next = head;

        ListNode fast = dummy;
        ListNode slow = dummy;

        for(int i = 0; i <= n; i++) {
            fast = fast.next;
        }

        while(fast != null) {
            fast = fast.next;
            slow = slow.next;
        }

        slow.next = slow.next.next;

        return dummy.next;
    }
}
